{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"afd1ab1a-0c30-46ab-8b6e-f14fd4f44d45","content":"No worries that the project doesn't exist yet — here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`dotnet run --project`** — builds and launches the server automatically.\n- Your MCP server must read JSON-RPC messages from stdin and write responses to stdout (no `Console.WriteLine` logging — use stderr instead).\n\nIf you've already published the server to a DLL, you can use `\"command\": \"dotnet\"` with `\"args\": [\"path/to/MyMcpServer.dll\"]` instead for faster startup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bde268c9-9389-445c-8863-92bbc206c960","outputTokens":287,"requestId":"AC1A:1BD058:BAB004:E64992:6A012D17"},"id":"40095aa6-2aa4-4d67-bc06-608448b69c9c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:13:04.132Z","parentId":"954a2438-f14a-46c6-9d12-c52c95aae0cc"}
